<subSubSection id="2FC0C85777AF65D64B4708B6AC67FA25" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph id="CF89052E7C72FA684D446EAB2E035E8D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="935A2FA50151FE1806DF0C8784C167C5" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="66B1D8AECD20CED4EB2434B22E732B09" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1858" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Mesembrius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesembrius ingratus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingratus">
<emphasis id="ADD91036A02BD6BDDE4D02ABAC0721F3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Mesembrius ingratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males are holoptic, have a loose black apical pile brush on the profemur, a densely yellow pilose scutum with vague longitudinal vittae, a tuft of black pile on the posterior side of the probasitarsus, a slender metatibia and a posterior deep depression in the proximal half of the metatibia which ventrally extends into a deep groove. It can be distinguished from any other species by the apical pile brush of the profemur which is loose and yellowish with some black pile interspersed (black dorsally, yellow ventrally in 
<taxonomicName id="202B0DEEB6849EA99501C5D9759D54EE" genus="M." lsidName="M. arcuatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="arcuatus">
<emphasis id="98551D7AF521616427CE66140694AFB9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. arcuatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov.; black in 
<taxonomicName id="36D54797AE48466DAF3720D3489076FA" genus="M." lsidName="M. tarsatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tarsatus">
<emphasis id="D9EF25DB144F5F70FEA41DF5486F98AF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. tarsatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and by the deep groove on the metatibia (strongly compressed in 
<taxonomicName id="550996B1B7B13ECAB0DDF6125DCB12CB" genus="M." lsidName="M. arcuatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="arcuatus">
<emphasis id="836BBD69C61779926D99FA43544C6873" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. arcuatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov.; with a rounded swelling in 
<taxonomicName id="144F74225F2ED6E6777243CECF15C005" genus="M." lsidName="M. tarsatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tarsatus">
<emphasis id="BC02D6854357B2870A1C94BDC92CFF8C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. tarsatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The female is unknown.
</paragraph>
